27/Jan/09 12:26 AM;triqui;I've been working with this for a while too and I found a couple of things that I think can help a little bit to understand the problem.

1. Adding a global transition on-exception for accessdenied is only advisable for flows which are not secured.
If a flow is secured and you aren't allowed to access it, an accessDenied will be thrown as you try to access the url linked with it. In that moment you cannot do anything to process that exception properly since access to that flow and all its states is locked, so the exception has to be passed on.
If a flow is not secured and you get an accessDenied exception, that means that you tried to access a secured "subflow" from the not secured flow. In that moment you can decide where to go since you are in an open flow and can redirect the request to the state you want.

2. Adding a state transition on-exception for accessdenied works perfectly for any flow. But, logically, it doesn't do anything for the current flow or state, but only when a transition to a restricted subflow happens.

3. To handle accessdenied exceptions when accessing restricted flows directly you can use ExceptionTranslationFilter, global exception-handlers or exception-handlers from current flow.
Exception-handlers is, in my opinion, the best option, since you have access to the current context and can redirect where you want based on which flow you are trying to access. Furthermore, you can define different handlers for different groups of flows to have a different action for each one, and have global handlers for every flow merged with other custom handlers for a given flow.
You can use the flowId stored in the FlowExecutionException passed to the exception-handler or access authentication details from the context which is also passed to the exception-handler or any other parameter from the context to decide where to go.
On the other hand, this flow exception handlers will be ignored if you define a transition on-exception or a exception-handler defined in a given view-state.


In conclussion: You can define a exception-handler in an abstract flow that you will inherit from when defining other flows.
You can define a custom exception-handler for a given flow and it will be merged with handlers inherited from parent flow.
You can define a global exception-handler for a given view state and make your view states inherit from that one.
You can define a custom exception-handler for a given view state in your flow and it will be merged with handlers inherited from parent state.
When you define a transition on-exception it is implemented using an internal exception-handler, so there is no difference between them.
View state exception handling is processed first and flow exception handling is only executed when the exception is not handled before.
Remember, of course, than ExceptionTranslationFilter will catch the AccessDeniedException if no other exception-handler handles it.
So there is a lot of options to catch an AccessDeniedException and handle it.

What I have is the following:
1. I defined an Access denied error page to go when everything else fails with ExceptionTranslationFilter.
2. I defined an abstract flow with a view state with a transition on-exception to="accessDenied" and a view state called accessDenied.
3. I inherit that view state when I want access denied to be redirected to another page.
4. I override the view from the accessDenied view state if I want to display a custom page for a given flow(s).
5. I created an AccessDeniedExceptionHandler that will build an access denied message, add it to current view state's context and reload the view state. If stateId is null then it will not handle the exception. I use this in some special cases when links are available to the user but the destination flows are restricted for his role.

public class AccessDeniedExceptionHandler implements FlowExecutionExceptionHandler {
	public boolean canHandle(FlowExecutionException fee) {
		return canHandleFlow(fee.getFlowId())
			&& canHandleState(fee.getFlowId(), fee.getStateId())
			&& findAccessDeniedException(fee) != null;
	}

	public boolean canHandleFlow(String flowId) {
		return true;
	}

	public boolean canHandleState(String flowId, String stateId) {
		return stateId != null;
	}

	public void handle(FlowExecutionException fee, RequestControlContext context) {
		MessageBuilder builder = new MessageBuilder().error();
		builder.code("security.error.accessDenied");
		builder.arg(context.getExternalContext().getCurrentUser());
		builder.arg(fee.getFlowId());
		builder.defaultText("You don't have access to the selected resource");
		context.getMessageContext().addMessage(builder.build());
		context.getExternalContext().requestFlowExecutionRedirect();
	}
}


This way I can handle access denied exceptions in many different ways depending only on what I inherit or not when defining a flow.

