27/Sep/08 10:29 AM;rstoya05-aop;DateTextBox exposes datePattern - an attribute Dojo uses for on-screen display only. What's actually used for accepting and sending the value to the server is ISO-8601 formatting. This is an issue for applications that want to customize the formatting used for exchanging a value with the server and at the same remain degradable.

Currently swf-booking-mvc shows how to parse the date from the server:
Spring.addDecoration(new Spring.ElementDecoration({
	elementId : "checkoutDate",
	widgetType : "dijit.form.DateTextBox",
	widgetAttrs : { 
		value : dojo.date.locale.parse(dojo.byId("checkoutDate").value, {selector : "date", datePattern : "yyyy-MM-dd"}), 
		required : true }}));  

On the other hand to send a custom date to the server the serialize method can be used:
Spring.addDecoration(new Spring.ElementDecoration({
	elementId : "checkoutDate",
	widgetType : "dijit.form.DateTextBox",
	widgetAttrs : { 
		value : dojo.date.locale.parse(dojo.byId("checkoutDate").value, {selector : "date", datePattern : "MM/dd/yyyy"}), 
		serialize : function(d, options){
			return dojo.date.locale.format(d, {selector : "date", datePattern : "MM/dd/yyyy"});
		},
		required : true }}));  

This works ok but amounts to a lot of boilerplate code. I've attached a patch to Spring-Dojo.js allowing this much shorter syntax:
Spring.addDecoration(new Spring.ElementDecoration({
	elementId : "checkoutDate",
	widgetType : "dijit.form.DateTextBox",
	widgetAttrs : {
		datePattern : "MM/dd/yyyy",
		required : true
	}}));

In effect the semantics of the DateTextBox datePattern attribute are extended so it is used not just for on-screen display but also for parsing and formatting the server value. This would be a nice value-add of Spring JS as it is almost certain that a degradable application might want to provide a custom date format.

Note that with the attached patch it is still possible to provide your own 'value' attribute and 'serialize' method.

