The scenario what I am explaining below is working with Spring Webflow PR5 version. When we upgraded to Spring Webflow 1.0 RC2, the same scenario is throwing null pointer exception at the dao layer.

We have a main flow and a subflow. The main flow is creating a form action subclass. This form action subclass is configured in Spring context file. At one point the main flow delegates the task to the subflow. The main flow passes information to the subflow including some service objects configured in the Spring context file. The sublflow form backing object is a POJO class that is not configured in Spring context file. This POJO is created explicitly in the java code and using some of its setter methods, the invoker of this POJO form backing object sets some of the service objects that are configured in Spring context file.

The main flow delgates to the subflow without any problem at all. The moment we do some operation that involves DAO (using Hibernate Template) within subflow, it throws null pointer exception at the method getHibernateTemplate() level. The interesting scenario we found is that all the service objects involved in the DAO operation are created again with a different hashcode than before. It makes sense not to create a seperate instance of HibernateTemplate as it is do with the persistence layer.

So I guess, the culprit is either on our side by creating the POJO class explicitly in the code and setting some of the DAO services explicitly using some of its setter methods instead of defer it to the Spring framework to create and inject the colloborating service objects. Or is it the new webflow not forgiving as it was in PR5 version. 

Please advice us accordingly. This is a critical bug and it is holding our production implementation.


