20/Jun/16 9:49 AM;kdvolder;Sorry it took me so long to get round to this. Finally I did :-)

So, your app cuts down a lot on the 'stuff' that a default spring-boot app autoconfigures. Unfortunately, you cut out the "Jmx" pieces that STS relies on to ask spring boot about some things about your app such as:
  - whether the app has started up
  - what port the app is running on
  - ask app to 'shutdown nicely' when you click on stop in STS dash. 

So this is what's throwing STS of and why that stuff isn't working. 

STS actually thinks your app should support these features because it is a recent enough version of spring-boot. But in fact it doesn't because those part of the spring-boot infra aren't enabled in your app.

I fixed this by adding these two to your ContextConfiguration class:

	JmxAutoConfiguration.class,
	SpringApplicationAdminJmxAutoConfiguration.class

I.e my fixed version look like this:

{noformat}
@Configuration
@ConditionalOnWebApplication
@Import({
	EmbeddedServletContainerAutoConfiguration.class, 
	ServerPropertiesAutoConfiguration.class, 
	DispatcherServletAutoConfiguration.class,
	JmxAutoConfiguration.class,
	SpringApplicationAdminJmxAutoConfiguration.class
})
public class ContextConfiguration extends WebMvcConfigurerAdapter {
}
{noformat}

After adding those the boot dash can correctly detect when your app has started.

If you don't want to add these to your app for whatever reason, then you can use the dash with reduced functionality. Just make sure to disable the "JMX" based features in the launch config of the app. I.e. click on the 'pencil' icon on the dash and uncheck "Enable Live Bean Support" and "Enable Life Cycle Management".

What this will do:
 - spinner will be non-existing (i.e. aps only have two states 'stopped' or 'running' there is no starting state in between.
 - the port of the app will be 'unknown' (unfortunately it also means the 'globe' icon to open web-page won't work since STS cannot determine what port the app is running on, so doesn't know how to compute local url of your app)

